<h2 style="text-align: center">CONSERVATION</h2>

<p>Conservation is an ethic of resource use, allocation, and protection. Its primary focus is upon maintaining the health of the natural world its, fisheries, habitats, and biological diversity.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conservation_(ethic))

<p><b>Types of Conservation: -</b> 
<p>There are 2 main types of conservations of conservation of environment and its living beings: -
<p margin>In-situ and Ex-situ conservation.

<p style="margin-left: 150px;">1. <b>In-situ Conservation: -</b> In-situ conservation, the conservation of species in their natural habitats, is considered the most appropriate way of conserving biodiversity.
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">Conserving the areas where populations of species exist naturally is an underlying condition for the conservation of biodiversity. That's why protected areas form a central element of any national strategy to conserve biodiversity. 
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.jamaicachm.org.jm/BHS/conservation.htm)

<p style="margin-left: 150px;">Institutions for in-situ conservation: - 
<p style="margin-left: 200px;">&#8226 <b>Wildlife Sanctuary: -</b> A wildlife refuge, also called a wildlife sanctuary, is a naturally occurring sanctuary, such as an island, that provides protection for species from hunting, predation or competition, it is a protected area, a geographic territory within which wildlife is protected.
<p style="text-align: right">(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wildlife_refuge)

\image image1
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 1. Wildlife Sanctuary
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.indianholiday.com/india-wildlife-holidays/kabini/)

<p style="margin-left: 200px;">&#8226 <b>National Parks: -</b> A national park is a park, in use for conservation purposes. Often it is a reserve of natural, semi-natural, or developed land that a sovereign state declares or owns.

\image image2
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 2. National Park
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_park)

<p style="margin-left: 200px;">&#8226 <b>Biosphere reserves: -</b> A biosphere reserve is a voluntary, cooperative, conservation reserve created to protect the biological and cultural diversity of a region while promoting sustainable economic development. Biosphere reserves serve in some ways as 'living laboratories' for testing out and demonstrating united management of land, water and biodiversity.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.nrdc.org/land/wilderness/fbios.asp)

\image image3
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 3. Biosphere Reserve
<p style="text-align: right">(https://www.mouthshut.com/product-reviews/Nilgiri-Biosphere-Reserve-Photos-925103849)

<p style="margin-left: 150px;">2. <b>Ex-situ Conservation: -</b> Ex-situ conservation is the preservation of components of biological diversity outside their natural habitats.  This involves conservation of genetic resources, as well as wild and cultivated species, and draws on a diverse body of techniques and facilities.  Some of these include:
<p style="margin-left: 200px;">&#8226 Gene banks, e.g. seed banks, sperm and ova banks, field banks;
<br>&#8226 In vitro plant tissue and microbial culture collections;
<br>&#8226 Captive breeding of animals and artificial propagation of plants, with possible reintroduction into the wild;
<br>&#8226 Collecting living organisms for zoos, aquaria, and botanic gardens for research and public awareness.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.jamaicachm.org.jm/BHS/conservation.htm)

<p><b>Importance of conservation</b>
<p>There is no evidence that natural resources may last longer. But evidences are submitted that these resources a few years only. So, to retain the ability of future generation and for the sake of other creatures, conservation of natural resources is significant.

<p><b>Critical State of Indian Forests</b>
<p>In India, population growth is a major problem. This results in clearing of forest areas for obtaining land for industrial, building, infrastructure, mining and agricultural purposes.

<p><i>"A 1999 publication claimed that protected forest areas in several parts of India, such as Jammu and Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh, Karnataka and Jharkhand, were vulnerable to illegal logging by timber mafias that have coopted or intimidated forestry officials, local politicians, businesses and citizenry. Clear-cutting is sometimes covered-up by conniving officials who report fictitious forest fires."	</i>
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forestry_in_India#Timber_mafia_and_forest_cover)

<p><b>Conflicts surrounding forested areas</b>
<p>Though not officially acknowledged, many of such forest areas covering more than 7 States of India including West Bengal, Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Bihar, Andhra Pradesh and Maharashtra have become hot-beds of armed conflicts of Maoists (an extremist organization). More than 6000 people have been killed during the 20-year fight of Maoists for a communist state. The Maoists are now operating in more than 223 districts of India with large tribal concentration through guerilla warfare tactics.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forestry_in_India)

<p><b>Populations and tribals and their rights</b>
<p>Millions of people live in and near India's forest lands, but have no legal right to their homes, lands or livelihoods. A few government officials have all the power over the forests and forest dwellers. The result? Both the forest and people die.
<p>An act was passed by the Indian government in 2006 in this context. It is called "Forests Rights Act". It recognizes the forest dwellers' rights and makes conservation accountable.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://forestrightsact.com/what-is-this-act-about)

<p><b>An introduction of this Act: -</b> 

<p><u>Land Rights</u>: - 
<p>There is no question of granting 4 hectares of land to every family.  If I am cultivating half a hectare on December 13, 2005, I receive title to that half a hectare alone; and if I am cultivating nothing, I receive nothing.  If I am cultivating more than 4 hectares without documents or a dispute, I receive title to only 4 hectares.

<p><u>Rights for the forest dwellers</u>: - 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">1. They can traditionally collect things like tendu patta, herbs, medicinal plants, etc.
<br>2. Grazing grounds and waterbodies
<br>3. Traditional areas of use by nomadic or pastoralist communities, that is, commodities which move with their herds.

<p><u>Right to Protection and Conserve</u>: - 
<p>Section 3(1)(i) provide a right and a power to conserve community forest resources, while section 5 gives the community a general power to protect wildlife, forests, etc.  This is vital for the thousands of village communities who are protecting their forests and wildlife against threats from forest mafias, industries and land grabbers, most of whom operate in connivance [involvement and participation] with the Forest Department. 
<p style="text-align: right">(http://forestrightsact.awardspace.com/intro.htm#mozTocId724590)

<p><b>Tourism: -</b> 
<p>The natural beauty of the forests is a gift given to us by Mother Nature. 'Sustainability' in simple terms means our responsibility to preserve and maintain the charms of nature, as it enables the next generation also to enjoy the same. Thus conservation of forests, our natural heritage, becomes most important, while practicing sustainable tourism.
<p>But when the topic comes that who should conserve and for whose profit, conflicts occur.
<p>The basic lack of cultural awareness about the places where tourists go also leads to cultural conflicts.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.tourindiakerala.com/tiger.html)
<br>(http://www.scribd.com/doc/30556098/Tourism-in-India-Role-in-Conflict-and-Peace)

<p><b>Poaching: -</b> 
<p>Illegal poaching of wildlife for oriental medicines, wood (timber), hides, rhino horns, elephant tusks, bear skin and bile, deer musk, and these products or raw materials increases man - animal conflict.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://projecttiger.nic.in/poaching.asp)

<p><b>Development Projects: -</b> 
<p>Various development projects are built at the cost of environment. Best examples are roads and dams.

<p><b>Roads: -</b> 
<p>Building roads may be a modern world development, but when roads are built by cutting trees, it is a great loss of environment of a country or region. Also, roads do not allow rain water to penetrate the ground and reach the underground water table.

<p><b>Dams: -</b> 
<p>While building dams whole forests of that particular area are flooded and get destroyed. Thousands of people have to leave their homes if in that area.
<p>In dams, there is a drawback of silting. And after a particular period of time, the dam is of no further use because of continuous deposition of silt carried by rivers.

\image image4
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 4. Dam
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.walkthroughindia.com/attraction/the-5-biggest-dams-in-india/)

<p><b>Overexploitation of forest resources: -</b> 
<p>Reforestation competes with other land uses such as food production, livestock grazing, and living space for further economic growth. Today, developed countries continue to utilize timber for building houses, and wood pulp for paper. In developing countries almost three billion people rely on wood for heating and cooking. Short-term economic gains made by conversion of forest to agriculture, or overexploitation of wood products, typically leads to loss of long-term income and long term biological productivity. 
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overexploitation)

<p><b>Scientific Forestry: -</b> 
<p>Scientific forestry today is "the art and science of managing forests, tree plantations, and related natural resources. The main goal is to create and implement systems that allow forests to continue a sustainable continuation of environmental supplies and services."

<p><br>The challenge is to create systems that are socially accepted while sustaining the any resource that might be affected.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://in.answers.yahoo.com/question/index?qid=20091023092910AAbWG7s)

<p><br>Scientific forestry program in India was started during the colonial period in 1864.
<br>In 1885, William Schlich, the then inspector general of India, established the Royal Engineering College at Cooper's Hill, in the south of England, in order to train students for Indian Forest Service.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.hindu.com/edu/2009/09/14/stories/2009091450870300.htm)

<p><b>Limitations of scientific forestry: -</b> 
<p>A few limitations of scientific forestry are: -
<p style="margin-left: 200px;">&#8226 Scientific Forest management systems are not readily understandable.
<br>&#8226 The knowledge of scientific forestry is linked with literacy and is confined with literate people only.
<br>&#8226 Insufficient utilization of indigenous forestry. Lack of literacy among indigenous forest managers.

<p><b>Social Forestry: -</b> 
<p>Social forestry means the management and protection of forests and afforestation on barren lands with the purpose of helping in the environmental, social and rural development.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_forestry_in_India)

