<p><b>(Case Study) Project Tiger: -</b> 

<p>'Project Tiger', a centrally sponsored scheme, was launched on April 1, 1973 to save tigers. Initially, the Project started with nine tiger reserves, covering an area of 16,339 sq km. with a population of 268 tigers. And at present there are 27 tiger reserves covering an area of 37,761 sq km. with a population of 1498 tigers.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.wildlifeofindia.org/projtiger.htm)

<p>WWF - India has been working towards tiger conservation, across India by: - 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">&#8226 Reducing poaching
<br>&#8226 Protecting tiger habitats and corridors
<br>&#8226 Minimizing illegal trade of tiger parts
<br>&#8226 Increasing awareness on tiger conservation

\image image6
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 6. Tiger
<p style="text-align: right">(http://support.wwfindia.org/tiger/)

<p><b>Failures: -</b>
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">&#8226 Project tiger directorate is merely a guiding authority having no judicial or quasi-judicial authority. It does not have the manpower to analyze the inputs and information from state reserves. It merely acts as an advisory body. In the current scenario an authority with legal power is needed.
<br>&#8226 There is an immense lack of coordination amongst the bodies dealing with project tiger. There is no intelligence gathering system and if there is some intelligence input, there does not exist an adequate action mechanism. The state Government does not release funds received from central funds on the time. There are about 15 tiger reserves which have the area less than the prescribed area for a tiger reserve.
<br>&#8226 Funds are released by the center on time but these funds are extremely insufficient. 
<br>&#8226 The forest department has not maintained healthy relations with communities inhabiting the peripheries of these reserves. No swift action is taken on the killing of livestock by tigers.
<p style="text-align: right">(https://www.facebook.com/notes/save-the-tiger/project-tiger-the-basic-facts-and-why-is-it-a-big-failure-the-destination-india-/493042757726)

<p><b>(Case Study) Project Elephant: -</b> 
<p>Project Elephant (PE) was launched by the Government of India in the year 1992 as a Centrally Sponsored Scheme with the following objectives: - 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">&#8226 protect elephants, their habitat & corridors
<br>&#8226 address issues of man-animal conflict
<br>&#8226 welfare of domesticated elephants 

\image image7
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 7. Elephants
<p style="text-align: right">(http://117.239.77.10/~forusr/wcpalakkad/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=121&Itemid=84)

<p>India is home to between 50 and 60% of all of Asia's wild elephants and about 20% of the domesticated elephants. As such, the country is of paramount importance for the survival of the species.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.eleaid.com/index.php?page=elephantsinindia)

<p>Failures: - 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">&#8226 Female Asian elephants are not affected by ivory poaching (due to their lack of tusks), so poaching has not affected the overall population numbers of Asian elephants as drastically.
<br>&#8226 Reasons for decline include persecution of wild elephants due to the crop damage they are perceived to cause, hunting (mainly for ivory but also for meat) and habitat loss due to expanding human population and the loss of forests in Asia.
<p style="text-align: right">(https://www.elephantnaturepark.org/)
